    summary: "The Federal Reserve opted to maintain its benchmark interest rate at 3.75 percent, citing persistent core inflation in the services sector despite easing commodity prices. Chair Williams signaled a cautious approach through the summer months.",
    body: `The Federal Reserve held its key interest rate unchanged at 3.75 percent on Wednesday, a decision that was widely anticipated by markets but accompanied by a statement that left the door open for a cut later this year. The central bank acknowledged that inflation had moderated in recent months but noted that core prices, particularly in housing and healthcare, remained "stubbornly elevated."\n\nFed Chair John Williams, speaking at a press conference following the decision, struck a careful balance between optimism and restraint. "The economy continues to show resilience," he said. "Labor markets remain strong, and consumer spending has held up. But we need to see more sustained progress on inflation before adjusting our policy stance."\n\nThe statement pointed to a split among committee members. The meeting minutes, which will be released in three weeks, are expected to reveal that at least two governors favored a quarter-point reduction, arguing that real interest rates are now sufficiently restrictive. Bond markets reflected this uncertainty, with the yield on the 10-year Treasury note dropping to 3.42 percent before settling at 3.48 percent by the close of trading.\n\nEconomists were divided in their interpretation. "This is a Fed that wants to cut but doesn't yet have the data to justify it," said Maria Chen, chief economist at Barclays. "We expect the June meeting to be the pivotal one." Others warned that the central bank risks overtightening. "The lag effects of monetary policy are real," wrote former Fed Governor Lael Brainard in a blog post. "Waiting too long could push unemployment above its natural rate."\n\nAll eyes now turn to next month's Consumer Price Index report, due May 14, which will be the last major data point before the Fed's June meeting.`,
