    category: "Sports",
    author: "Diego Ramirez",
    date: "2026-04-08",
    summary: "With the 2026 FIFA World Cup just weeks away, here's everything you need to know about the tournament being held across the United States, Canada, and Mexico. The expanded 48-team format promises the biggest edition in the sport's history.",
    body: `The 2026 FIFA World Cup kicks off on June 11 with a tournament unlike any before it. Spread across 16 host cities in three countries, the first-ever 48-team World Cup will feature 104 matches played over 39 days, culminating in the final at MetLife Stadium in East Rutherford, New Jersey, on July 19.\n\nThe expansion from 32 to 48 teams means more nations than ever will taste football's grandest stage. Newcomers include Indonesia, which qualified for the first time in the country's history, as well as Iceland, Bahrain, and Tanzania. The group stage has been restructured into 12 groups of four, with the top two and eight best third-placed teams advancing to a 32-team knockout round.\n\nHost cities range from Vancouver and Toronto in Canada, to Guadalajara and Mexico City in Mexico, to a dozen American venues including Los Angeles, Dallas, Miami, Atlanta, Houston, Philadelphia, Seattle, San Francisco, Boston, Kansas City, Nashville, and New York/New Jersey. Organizers estimate that more than 5.5 million fans will attend matches in person, shattering previous records.\n\nLogistical challenges remain significant. Transportation between venues, cross-border travel requirements, and the sheer scale of security operations have drawn criticism from some quarters. FIFA President Gianni Infantino has pushed back against skeptics, calling the tournament "a celebration of global unity through sport." Ticket prices have also been a point of contention, with general admission seats for group stage matches starting at $65 and final tickets reaching $1,500.\n\nOn the pitch, the favorites are familiar: Brazil, France, Argentina, and England head most analysts' shortlists. But the expanded format increases the probability of upsets, and dark horses like Japan, Nigeria, and the United States — playing before a home crowd — could make deep runs. The tournament will also be the first under new offside rules, which allow for a wider margin of error using semi-automated detection technology.`,
