    title: "EU Passes Sweeping AI Regulation, Setting Global Precedent",
    category: "Science",
    author: "Lena Johansson",
    date: "2026-04-11",
    summary: "The European Parliament has approved the AI Act's final implementation rules, establishing the world's most comprehensive framework for artificial intelligence governance. Companies face steep fines for non-compliance starting in October.",
    body: `The European Parliament voted overwhelmingly on Thursday to approve the final implementation rules of the AI Act, bringing to a close a legislative process that began in 2021. The rules, which take full effect on October 1, will require companies deploying artificial intelligence systems in the EU to meet strict transparency, safety, and accountability standards.\n\nUnder the framework, AI systems are classified into four risk tiers. Those deemed to pose "unacceptable risk" — including social scoring systems and real-time biometric surveillance in public spaces — are banned outright. "High-risk" applications, such as AI used in hiring decisions, credit scoring, law enforcement, and medical devices, must undergo rigorous third-party audits and maintain detailed documentation. General-purpose AI models with systemic reach, like large language models, face additional disclosure requirements around training data and energy consumption.\n\nFines for non-compliance are severe: up to 35 million euros or seven percent of global annual revenue, whichever is higher. "This is Europe leading the way," said Dragos Tudorache, the Romanian MEP who co-led the parliamentary effort. "We are showing that innovation and regulation are not enemies. They are partners."\n\nTech industry reactions have been mixed. European startups broadly welcomed the clarity, while American tech giants expressed concern about compliance costs. A spokesperson for Meta said the company was "reviewing the final text" and would "work constructively" with regulators. OpenAI, which has a significant European user base, said it had already begun modifying its systems to meet the new requirements.\n\nThe legislation is expected to influence regulators worldwide. Brazil, India, and South Korea are all considering AI governance frameworks that borrow elements from the EU approach. In Washington, the Biden-era AI executive orders remain in effect, but congressional action on comprehensive legislation has stalled amid partisan disagreements over the scope of federal authority.`,
