    title: "Rising Sea Levels Threaten Coastal Cities: What Experts Say We Must Do Now",
    category: "Science",
    author: "Priya Sharma",
    date: "2026-03-28",
    summary: "A new IPCC report warns that sea levels could rise by up to 1.5 meters by 2100 under current emission trajectories. Coastal megacities from Miami to Mumbai face existential threats without immediate action.",
    body: `A special report released this week by the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change paints a stark picture of the future facing the world's coastal regions. Under current emission trajectories, global sea levels are projected to rise between 0.7 and 1.5 meters by the end of the century, with some scenarios suggesting even higher increases if ice sheet instabilities in Antarctica accelerate beyond current models.\n\nThe consequences would be devastating. Approximately 900 million people live in low-lying coastal areas, and many of the world's largest cities — including Shanghai, Lagos, Jakarta, New York, and Mumbai — would face regular flooding, saltwater intrusion into freshwater supplies, and in some cases, partial submersion. The economic cost is estimated in the tens of trillions of dollars.\n\n"This is not a distant future problem," said Dr. Elena Vasquez, lead author of the report and a climate scientist at the Potsdam Institute for Climate Impact Research. "We are seeing the early effects already. The question is whether we adapt now, at manageable cost, or wait and face catastrophic expense."\n\nThe report outlines a range of adaptation strategies, from traditional sea walls and levees to nature-based solutions such as mangrove restoration and wetland preservation. It also calls for managed retreat from the most vulnerable areas — a politically explosive recommendation that has met resistance from property developers and local governments. In the United States, the Federal Emergency Management Agency has begun updating flood zone maps for the first time in a decade, a process that will affect insurance premiums and building codes for millions of properties.\n\nPerhaps the most consequential finding is that aggressive emissions cuts made now could limit sea level rise to under one meter by 2100, buying crucial time for adaptation. "Every fraction of a degree matters," said Dr. Vasquez. "Every delay costs lives."`,
