    category: "Business",
    author: "Rachel Whitman",
    date: "2026-04-09",
    summary: "New data from the National Association of Realtors shows median home prices in 30 major metropolitan areas have risen 8.4 percent year-over-year. Economists warn that a generation of young Americans may be permanently locked out of homeownership.",
    body: `The American housing market shows few signs of cooling, according to data released Tuesday by the National Association of Realtors. The median existing home price across 30 major metropolitan areas reached $438,000 in March, an 8.4 percent increase from the same month last year and a new record. In cities like Austin, Nashville, and Boise, prices have risen even faster, driven by continued migration from higher-cost coastal markets.\n\nThe affordability squeeze is most acute for first-time buyers. With mortgage rates hovering near 6.5 percent, the monthly payment on a median-priced home now requires a household income of approximately $105,000 — well above the national median of $78,000. Down payment requirements have also risen, as lenders tighten standards in response to elevated delinquency rates among recent buyers.\n\n"We are watching a generational divide harden in real time," said Dr. Jenny Schuetz, a housing economist at the Brookings Institution. "Without significant policy intervention, millions of Americans under 40 will spend their prime earning years as renters, missing out on the wealth-building benefits of homeownership."\n\nThe supply side of the equation remains constrained. New housing starts declined 3.1 percent in February, as builders grapple with high material costs, labor shortages, and restrictive zoning in many suburban municipalities. Federal efforts to encourage construction, including tax credits for affordable housing developers, have been slow to translate into units on the ground.\n\nSome cities are experimenting with innovative approaches. Minneapolis eliminated single-family zoning in 2019, and early data suggests the policy has modestly increased housing production. Oregon and California have passed similar laws. But opponents warn that densification threatens neighborhood character, and political resistance remains fierce in many communities.`,
