    category: "Science",
    author: "Yuki Tanaka",
    date: "2026-04-05",
    summary: "JR Central has revealed the ALFA-X successor, a maglev-hybrid bullet train that combines conventional high-speed rail with magnetic levitation technology. Commercial service between Tokyo and Osaka is targeted for 2031.",
    body: `Japan Rail Central on Saturday unveiled the N700-Supreme, a next-generation shinkansen that represents a radical leap in high-speed rail technology. The train, displayed at a ceremony in Hamamatsu, combines elements of conventional wheel-on-rail technology with partial magnetic levitation, allowing it to reach speeds of 400 kilometers per hour while maintaining the reliability and ride comfort that have defined Japan's bullet train network for six decades.\n\nThe N700-Supreme uses a hybrid propulsion system developed over the past decade. At speeds below 200 km/h, the train operates on conventional rails. Above that threshold, superconducting magnets engage to partially lift the cars, reducing friction and enabling the dramatic speed increase. The transition between modes is seamless, according to engineers, with passengers experiencing no perceptible change.\n\n"This technology bridges the gap between today's shinkansen and tomorrow's fully maglev systems," said JR Central President Shin Kaneko. "It allows us to use existing rail infrastructure while delivering transformative speed improvements." The Tokyo-Osaka journey time, currently about two hours and 15 minutes, would shrink to approximately 75 minutes.\n\nThe project has drawn international attention. European rail operators Eurostar and Deutsche Bahn have expressed interest in licensing the technology for routes where full maglev construction is financially prohibitive. India, which is building its first bullet train line between Mumbai and Ahmedabad with Japanese assistance, has inquired about future compatibility.\n\nCommercial service is targeted for 2031, pending safety certification. Test runs on a dedicated track in Yamanashi Prefecture will begin later this year. The estimated cost of upgrading the Tokaido Shinkansen line for the new system is $30 billion, a figure that has prompted debate in the Japanese Diet about infrastructure spending priorities.`,
