    category: "Health",
    author: "Dr. Fatima Al-Rashid",
    date: "2026-04-07",
    summary: "The World Health Organization has officially ended its mpox public health emergency designation, citing a 94 percent decline in global cases. However, officials stress that surveillance and vaccination must continue.",
    body: `The World Health Organization on Tuesday formally ended the Public Health Emergency of International Concern designation for mpox, nearly two years after the most recent outbreak prompted global alarm. Global case counts have fallen 94 percent from their peak, with fewer than 200 confirmed cases reported worldwide in March.\n\n"This is a testament to the power of coordinated public health action," said WHO Director-General Dr. Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus at a press briefing in Geneva. "But ending the emergency does not mean ending our vigilance. The virus has not disappeared, and it will exploit any gap in our defenses."\n\nThe decline in cases has been attributed to several factors: widespread vaccination campaigns in at-risk communities, improved surveillance and contact tracing, and natural immunity from prior infection. The Jynneos vaccine, originally developed for smallpox, proved highly effective against mpox, and over 40 million doses have been administered globally since 2022.\n\nHowever, public health experts warn of persistent vulnerabilities. Vaccination rates in sub-Saharan Africa remain low, despite the region bearing a disproportionate burden of cases. Funding for mpox research and surveillance has also declined as political attention has shifted. "We've seen this pattern before with Ebola and Zika," said Dr. Anne Rimoin, a professor of epidemiology at UCLA. "The world rushes to respond during a crisis and then forgets until the next one."\n\nThe WHO is urging countries to maintain genomic surveillance for new mpox variants and to integrate mpox vaccination into routine immunization programs for high-risk populations. A next-generation vaccine, developed by Bavarian Nordic and offering single-dose protection, is expected to receive regulatory approval by late 2026.`,
