    title: "Ukraine and Russia Agree to Ceasefire Framework After Marathon Negotiations",
    category: "World",
    author: "Alexei Volkov",
    date: "2026-04-13",
    summary: "After two weeks of intensive talks in Istanbul, Ukrainian and Russian negotiators have agreed on a framework for a ceasefire and phased withdrawal. The deal, brokered by Turkey and the UN, is the most significant diplomatic breakthrough since the conflict began.",
    body: `Ukrainian and Russian delegations emerged from a fortified conference center in Istanbul late Saturday to announce what diplomats are calling the most substantial progress toward peace since the war began in February 2022. The framework agreement outlines a phased ceasefire, a demilitarized buffer zone along the current line of contact, and a series of confidence-building measures to be implemented over six months.\n\nThe deal, brokered by Turkish President Recep Tayyip Erdogan and U.N. Special Envoy Miroslav Lajcak, stops short of a final peace treaty. Critical issues — including the status of Crimea, the future of the occupied Donbas territories, and security guarantees for Ukraine — are deferred to a subsequent negotiation track. But the agreement commits both sides to an immediate cessation of hostilities, to be monitored by a multinational observer force.\n\n"We have taken the first step back from the abyss," said Ukrainian Foreign Minister Dmytro Kuleba, who led his country's delegation. "This is not the peace we sought, but it is the silence our people desperately need." His Russian counterpart, Sergei Lavrov, was more cautious: "The framework reflects reality. Whether it holds will depend on actions, not words."\n\nInternational reaction was swift. U.S. President Biden called it "a hopeful sign" but cautioned that sanctions on Russia would remain in place until a comprehensive peace is achieved. European Commission President Roberta Metsola pledged continued support for Ukraine's reconstruction. China's Foreign Ministry said it "welcomed the progress" and stood ready to contribute to peacekeeping efforts.\n\nThe agreement must still be ratified by both governments, and skeptics note that previous diplomatic efforts have collapsed. Hardliners in Moscow and Kyiv have already criticized the terms. But for the millions of civilians who have endured years of conflict, the framework represents something that has been in desperately short supply: hope.`,
