    title: "Breakthrough Gene Therapy Reverses Type 1 Diabetes in Clinical Trial",
    category: "Health",
    author: "Dr. Sarah Linfield",
    date: "2026-04-04",
    summary: "A Phase II clinical trial at Johns Hopkins has shown that a novel gene therapy can restore insulin production in patients with Type 1 diabetes. Twelve of 15 participants achieved insulin independence within six months.",
    body: `Researchers at Johns Hopkins University School of Medicine have published results from a Phase II clinical trial that could transform the treatment of Type 1 diabetes. The therapy, designated JH-4019, uses an adeno-associated virus vector to deliver functioning copies of key regulatory genes to pancreatic beta cells, effectively reprogramming the immune system to stop attacking insulin-producing tissue.\n\nOf the 15 participants in the trial, 12 achieved complete insulin independence within six months of treatment, meaning they no longer required daily injections to manage their blood sugar. The remaining three showed significant reductions in their insulin requirements. No serious adverse events were reported during the 18-month follow-up period.\n\n"These results exceeded our most optimistic projections," said Dr. Michael Kaplan, the lead investigator and a professor of endocrinology at Johns Hopkins. "For the first time, we have demonstrated that it is possible to durably reverse the autoimmune process that causes Type 1 diabetes. This is not a treatment — it is, we believe, a functional cure."\n\nType 1 diabetes affects approximately 8.4 million people worldwide and typically requires lifelong insulin therapy. Unlike Type 2 diabetes, which is linked to lifestyle factors, Type 1 is an autoimmune condition that usually manifests in childhood. Current management strategies, including insulin pumps and continuous glucose monitors, have improved quality of life but carry significant costs and burdens.\n\nThe trial results, published in the New England Journal of Medicine, have sent shockwaves through the medical community. Shares of Vertex Pharmaceuticals, which licensed the underlying technology, rose 18 percent on the news. A Phase III trial involving 200 participants across multiple sites is expected to begin enrollment in September, with FDA approval potentially following by 2028.`,
