    category: "Politics",
    author: "Min-jun Park",
    date: "2026-04-10",
    summary: "The Democratic Party of Korea has secured a commanding majority in Wednesday's parliamentary elections, dealing a severe blow to the ruling conservative party. The result is expected to reshape the country's domestic and foreign policy agenda.",
    body: `South Korea's main opposition Democratic Party won a decisive victory in parliamentary elections on Wednesday, capturing 178 of 300 seats in the National Assembly — a supermajority that gives the party the power to override presidential vetoes and even initiate constitutional amendments. The ruling People Power Party won just 98 seats, its worst performance in a decade.\n\nThe result reflects deep public frustration with the current government's handling of the economy, a corruption scandal involving senior aides to President Yoon Suk-yeol's successor, and a perception that the ruling party has been out of touch with ordinary citizens' concerns, particularly around housing costs and youth unemployment.\n\nDemocratic Party leader Lee Jae-myung, speaking to jubilant supporters at the party headquarters in Seoul, promised a "new era of governance." He outlined priorities including expanded social welfare programs, tougher regulations on chaebols — the large family-run conglomerates that dominate the Korean economy — and a more conciliatory approach to North Korea.\n\nThe foreign policy implications are significant. The incoming parliamentary majority is expected to push for renewed engagement with Pyongyang, potentially creating friction with Washington at a time when the U.S.-South Korea alliance is navigating complex regional dynamics. Analysts also note that the Democratic Party's skepticism toward closer military ties with Japan could complicate trilateral security cooperation.\n\n"This election is a clear mandate for change," said Professor Kang Won-taek, a political scientist at Seoul National University. "But governing with a supermajority brings its own challenges. The Democratic Party will need to demonstrate that it can deliver results, not just rhetoric."`,
