    title: "The Best Mediterranean Destinations for Summer 2026",
    category: "Culture",
    author: "Isabella Ferrero",
    date: "2026-03-25",
    summary: "From the unspoiled Albanian Riviera to the timeless beauty of Puglia, these Mediterranean destinations offer the best of sun, culture, and gastronomy while avoiding the worst of the summer crowds.",
    body: `As summer approaches, seasoned travelers are looking beyond the usual Mediterranean hotspots to discover destinations that offer authentic experiences without the crushing crowds. This year's standout picks blend natural beauty, rich history, and extraordinary cuisine in settings that feel refreshingly undiscovered.\n\nAlbania's Riviera continues its rise as one of Europe's best-kept secrets. The stretch of coastline from Vlore to Sarande features crystalline waters rivaling anything in Greece or Croatia, with a fraction of the tourist infrastructure — and the prices to match. The village of Dhermi, perched on a hillside above a stunning beach, has attracted a handful of boutique hotels and excellent seafood restaurants. Albania's investment in road infrastructure has also made the region far more accessible than it was even two years ago.\n\nIn Italy, Puglia remains the country's most compelling alternative to the Amalfi Coast and Cinque Terre. The heel of the Italian boot offers whitewashed hill towns, ancient olive groves, and a culinary tradition rooted in simplicity and extraordinary ingredients. Lecce, the "Florence of the South," has a baroque historic center that rewards hours of aimless wandering, while the beaches of the Salento peninsula are among the finest in the country.\n\nGreece's Peloponnese peninsula is another strong choice for 2026. While Santorini and Mykonos groan under the weight of overtourism, the Peloponnese offers ancient ruins, mountain villages, and unspoiled beaches in relative tranquility. The fortified town of Monemvasia, built into a massive rock island, is one of the most atmospheric places in all of Greece.\n\nFor those willing to venture slightly further afield, Montenegro's Bay of Kotor and Turkey's Lycian coast round out our recommendations. Both offer exceptional value, stunning landscapes, and a sense of discovery that the more established destinations struggle to provide.`,
