    id: 15,
    title: "How to Protect Your Mental Health in the Age of Information Overload",
    category: "Health",
    author: "Dr. Amelia Worth",
    date: "2026-03-20",
    summary: "Psychologists say the constant barrage of news, social media, and notifications is taking a measurable toll on mental health. Here are evidence-based strategies to stay informed without becoming overwhelmed.",
    body: `In an era when the average American checks their phone 144 times per day and is exposed to more information before breakfast than a medieval person encountered in a lifetime, psychologists are raising the alarm about the mental health consequences of what they call "information overload syndrome." The condition, which manifests as chronic anxiety, difficulty concentrating, and a pervasive sense of helplessness, has become so widespread that some clinicians consider it a public health issue.\n\n"Our brains evolved to process a village's worth of information," said Dr. Gloria Mark, a professor of informatics at the University of California, Irvine, and author of the book Attention Span. "We're asking them to process a planet's worth, and they're breaking down under the strain."\n\nResearch published in the journal JAMA Psychiatry in February found that people who consume more than three hours of news per day are 40 percent more likely to report symptoms of anxiety and depression than those who limit their intake to under 30 minutes. The effect is strongest for social media-delivered news, where algorithmic amplification of emotionally charged content creates what psychologists call "doom scrolling spirals."\n\nSo what can you do? Experts recommend several evidence-based strategies. First, designate specific times for news consumption — ideally no more than twice daily, and never within an hour of bedtime. Second, curate your information sources ruthlessly, prioritizing in-depth reporting over breaking news alerts. Third, practice "information hygiene" by turning off non-essential notifications and removing social media apps from your phone's home screen.\n\nPerhaps most importantly, experts stress the value of what they call "analog time" — regular periods of complete disconnection from digital devices. "Go for a walk without your phone," advises Dr. Mark. "Read a physical book. Have a conversation face to face. These activities don't just reduce stress — they restore the cognitive capacities that constant connectivity erodes."`,
