    summary: "TSMC has committed to a massive expansion of its Arizona semiconductor fabrication complex, adding three new facilities that will produce the company's most advanced 2-nanometer chips. The investment is the largest single foreign investment in U.S. manufacturing history.",
    body: `Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company, the world's largest contract chipmaker, announced on Friday a $40 billion expansion of its fabrication complex in Phoenix, Arizona, in what would be the largest single foreign investment in American manufacturing history. The expansion will add three new fabrication plants to the two already under construction, with the new facilities producing chips using TSMC's most advanced 2-nanometer process technology.\n\nThe announcement was made at a ceremony attended by President Biden, Commerce Secretary Gina Raimondo, and TSMC Chairman Mark Liu. Under the deal, TSMC will receive an additional $8 billion in federal subsidies and tax credits under the CHIPS and Science Act, on top of the $6.6 billion already committed for the first phase of the Arizona project.\n\n"This investment secures America's position in the most critical technology of the 21st century," said President Biden. "Semiconductors power everything from your phone to your car to our national defense. Having cutting-edge chips made on American soil is not just an economic priority — it is a national security imperative."\n\nThe expanded complex is expected to employ over 12,000 workers directly and support an estimated 40,000 additional jobs in the surrounding supply chain. Production at the first two plants is scheduled to begin in late 2026 and early 2027, while the three new facilities will come online between 2028 and 2030.\n\nThe investment reflects the broader geopolitical imperative driving semiconductor reshoring. TSMC currently manufactures over 90 percent of the world's most advanced chips at facilities in Taiwan, an island that faces an ongoing military threat from China. Diversifying production to the United States, Japan, and Germany reduces the risk of a catastrophic disruption to the global chip supply.\n\nAnalysts at Bernstein Research estimated that the Arizona complex, once fully operational, would produce approximately 15 percent of the world's most advanced chips, significantly reducing — though not eliminating — the concentration risk in Taiwan. "This doesn't solve the problem entirely," wrote analyst Stacy Rasgon, "but it materially improves the resilience of the global semiconductor supply chain."`,
